<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="283" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1866,2035]" pageId="6" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1938,1963]" pageId="6" pageNumber="283">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The following combination of characters is distinctive of 
<taxonomicName box="[999,1102,1940,1963]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azteca">
<emphasis box="[999,1102,1940,1963]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="283">P. azteca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: lower quarter or less of the frons orange (
<figureCitation box="[314,384,1974,1999]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1231,1253]" captionTargetBox="[229,1361,451,1207]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[222,1365,447,1209]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Prochyliza nigricoxa (Melander &amp; Spuler), Prochyliza brevicornis Melander, Prochyliza azteca McAlpine, Prochyliza inca McAlpine and Prochyliza lundbecki (Duda). (A) P. nigricoxa, male head, lateral view; (B) P. brevicornis, male head, laterofrontal view; (C) P. azteca, female head, lateraofrontal view; (D) P. i nc a, male epandrium, laterodorsal view, sp = spines on the epandrium; (E) P. lundbecki, male mid tibia, highlighting the posteroventral brush of yellowish hairs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224987/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="283">
Fig. 
<number box="[370,384,1974,1999]" pageId="6" pageNumber="283" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C); gena black; front coxa, mid and hind femora and mid and hind tibiae entirely yellow; margins and fringes of calypters white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="284" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">Remarks.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[480,679,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1977) A revised classification of the Piophilidae, including ' Neottiophilidae' and ' Thyreophoridae' (Diptera: Schizophora). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 103, 1 - 66. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 109103 fv" type="journal article" year="1977">
McAlpine (
<number box="[611,671,152,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="1977.0">1977</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, the two strictly Neotropical species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName box="[1257,1358,153,176]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azteca">
<emphasis box="[1257,1358,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. azteca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. inca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, were derived from the Holarctic fauna. 
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[685,884,188,213]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1977) A revised classification of the Piophilidae, including ' Neottiophilidae' and ' Thyreophoridae' (Diptera: Schizophora). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 103, 1 - 66. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 109103 fv" type="journal article" year="1977">
McAlpine (
<number box="[818,876,188,212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="1977.0">1977</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
also suggested that 
<emphasis box="[1126,1203,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. i nc a</emphasis>
would be the most closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[356,457,225,248]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azteca">
<emphasis box="[356,457,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. azteca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the morphology of the male of 
<emphasis box="[953,1051,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. az t e ca</emphasis>
remains undescribed, so it is not possible to know if this species shares with 
<taxonomicName box="[639,715,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">
<emphasis box="[639,715,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. inca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the extremely distinctive two horn-like spines on the epandrium (
<figureCitation box="[159,226,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1231,1253]" captionTargetBox="[229,1361,451,1207]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[222,1365,447,1209]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Prochyliza nigricoxa (Melander &amp; Spuler), Prochyliza brevicornis Melander, Prochyliza azteca McAlpine, Prochyliza inca McAlpine and Prochyliza lundbecki (Duda). (A) P. nigricoxa, male head, lateral view; (B) P. brevicornis, male head, laterofrontal view; (C) P. azteca, female head, lateraofrontal view; (D) P. i nc a, male epandrium, laterodorsal view, sp = spines on the epandrium; (E) P. lundbecki, male mid tibia, highlighting the posteroventral brush of yellowish hairs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224987/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,226,295,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="284" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,332,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">Biology.</emphasis>
The larvae are necrophagous. 
<bibRefCitation author="Jiron" box="[647,895,332,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" refString="Jiron, L. F. &amp; Cartin, V. M. (1981) Insect succession in the decomposition of a mammal in Costa Rica. Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 89, 158 - 165." type="journal article" year="1981">
Jirón &amp; Cartín (
<number box="[829,887,332,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="1981.0">1981</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
collected both adults and larvae on a dead dog during the dry season in a secondary forest of San José, 
<collectingCountry box="[778,903,367,392]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, highlighting that 
<emphasis box="[1107,1202,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. a z t ec a</emphasis>
was one of the most abundant insect species during most part of the decomposition process. The experiment of 
<bibRefCitation author="Jiron" box="[1188,1436,404,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" refString="Jiron, L. F. &amp; Cartin, V. M. (1981) Insect succession in the decomposition of a mammal in Costa Rica. Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 89, 158 - 165." type="journal article" year="1981">
Jirón &amp; Cartín (
<number box="[1370,1428,404,428]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="1981.0">1981</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
was carried out in the campus of the University of 
<collectingCountry box="[770,900,439,464]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, meaning that 
<taxonomicName box="[1079,1184,441,464]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azteca">
<emphasis box="[1079,1184,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">P. azteca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have developed synanthropic tendencies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="284" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,511,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">Distribution.</emphasis>
Neotropical; described from southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[841,926,511,536]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">México</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[943,1127,511,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1977) A revised classification of the Piophilidae, including ' Neottiophilidae' and ' Thyreophoridae' (Diptera: Schizophora). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 103, 1 - 66. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 109103 fv" type="journal article" year="1977">
McAlpine 
<number box="[1068,1127,512,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="1977.0">1977</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), it has been also recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[212,335,548,573]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jiron" box="[349,576,548,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" refString="Jiron, L. F. &amp; Cartin, V. M. (1981) Insect succession in the decomposition of a mammal in Costa Rica. Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 89, 158 - 165." type="journal article" year="1981">
Jirón &amp; Cartín 
<number box="[519,576,548,572]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry box="[639,728,548,572]" name="Panama" pageId="7" pageNumber="284">Panamá</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ozerov" box="[742,1033,548,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" refString="Ozerov, A. L. &amp; Norrbom, A. L. (2010) Piophilidae (skipper flies). In: Brown, B. V., Borkent, A., Cumming, J. M., Wood, D. M., Woodley, N. E. &amp; Zumbado, M. (Eds.), Manual of Central American Diptera. Vol. 2. National Research Council Press, Ottawa, pp. 865 - 869. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1899 / 30.3. br. 868" type="book" year="2010">
Ozerov &amp; Norrbom 
<number box="[972,1033,548,572]" pageId="7" pageNumber="284" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
